  "prompt": "I wanna start preparing for ias exam, how should I proceed?",
  "response": "Okay, that's a great goal! Preparing for the IAS (Indian Administrative Service) exam requires a structured and dedicated approach. Here's a comprehensive guide to help you get started:\n\n**I. Understanding the Exam:**\n\n*   **Official Notification:**\n    *   Download and thoroughly read the official notification released by the UPSC (Union Public Service Commission) for the Civil Services Examination. This is your bible!  It contains details about eligibility criteria, the exam pattern, syllabus, important dates, rules, and regulations.  Find it on the UPSC website (upsc.gov.in).\n*   **Exam Structure:**  The IAS exam (Civil Services Examination) has three stages:\n    *   **Preliminary Exam (Objective):**\n        *   Two papers:\n            *   **General Studies Paper I:**  Covers Indian History, Geography, Polity, Economy, Current Affairs, Environment, Science & Technology.  *Crucial for qualifying*.\n            *   **General Studies Paper II (CSAT - Civil Services Aptitude Test):**  Comprehension, Logical Reasoning & Analytical Ability, Decision-Making & Problem-Solving, General Mental Ability, Basic Numeracy, Data Interpretation.  *Qualifying only* (you need to score 33% to pass).\n    *   **Main Exam (Written & Interview):**\n        *   **Written Exam:** Nine papers in total.\n            *   **Qualifying Papers:**\n                *   Paper A:  One of the Indian Languages (as per the Eighth Schedule of the Constitution)\n                *   Paper B:  English\n            *   **Papers Counted for Merit:**\n                *   Essay\n                *   General Studies I: Indian Heritage & Culture, History & Geography of the World & Society.\n                *   General Studies II: Governance, Constitution, Polity, Social Justice & International relations.\n                *",
